.\" Render with:  man -l man/stryke.1
.\" Install:      cp man/stryke.1 /usr/local/share/man/man1/  (or $MANPATH/man1/)
.TH STRYKE 1 "June 2026" "stryke 0.16.20" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
stryke, s \- highly parallel Perl 5 interpreter with shell-grade REPL
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B s
[\fIOPTION\fR]... [\fB--\fR] [\fIPROGRAMFILE\fR] [\fIARGUMENT\fR]...
.br
.B s
\fICODE\fR
.br
.B s
.B -e
\fICODE\fR
.br
.B s
.I BUILTIN
[\fIARGS\fR...]
.br
.B s
.I SUBCOMMAND
[\fIARGS\fR...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B stryke
is a single-binary Perl 5 interpreter written in Rust, with parallel
extensions (pmap / pgrep / pfor / psort / preduce), a Cranelift JIT,
pipe-forward (\fB|>\fR) syntax, the thread macro (\fB~>\fR), and a
shell-grade REPL exposing 10,296 builtins as immediately-callable
barewords (no \fBuse\fR / \fBrequire\fR / \fBimport\fR).
.PP
The binary is invoked as \fBs\fR by default; \fBstryke\fR and \fBst\fR
are alternate spellings.
.PP
When called with one argument that looks like code, the
\fB-e\fR is optional (\fBs 'p "hi"'\fR works). When called with a known
builtin name plus arguments, stryke invokes that builtin directly
(\fBs basename /a/b\fR returns \fIb\fR), enabling stryke to be used as
a coreutils-style command launcher.
.SH EXECUTION
.TP
\fB'\fR\fICODE\fR\fB'\fR
Inline code; \fB-e\fR is optional when the argument looks like code.
.TP
.B -e \fICODE\fR
Explicit inline; required with \fB-n\fR, \fB-p\fR, \fB-l\fR, \fB-a\fR.
.TP
.B -E \fICODE\fR
Like \fB-e\fR but enables all optional features.
.TP
.IB BUILTIN " [" ARGS "]"
Call a builtin function directly from the shell. Example:
\fBs len 'hello'\fR, \fBs sha256 myfile\fR.
.TP
.B --script
Force script lookup when name conflicts with a builtin.
.TP
.B -c
Check syntax only; parse without compile/run.
.TP
.BR --lint ", " --check
Parse and compile bytecode without running.
.TP
.BR --disasm ", " --disassemble
Print bytecode disassembly to stderr before VM run.
.TP
.B --ast
Dump parsed AST as JSON and exit (no execution).
.TP
.B --fmt
Pretty-print parsed Perl to stdout and exit.
.TP
.B --explain \fICODE\fR
Print expanded hint for an error code (e.g. \fBE0001\fR) and exit.
.TP
.B --profile
Wall-clock profile to stderr (VM op lines; flamegraph-ready).
.TP
.B --flame
Flamegraph: terminal bars (TTY) or SVG (piped to file).
.TP
.B --no-jit
Disable Cranelift JIT (bytecode interpreter only).
.TP
.B --compat
Perl 5 strict-compat: disable all stryke extensions.
.TP
.B --no-interop
Reject Perl-isms (\fBsub\fR, \fBsay\fR, \fBreverse\fR, \fB$a\fR/\fB$b\fR);
force idiomatic stryke (\fB$_0\fR/\fB$_1\fR).
.TP
.B -d\fR[\fBt\fR][\fI:MOD\fR]
Run program under debugger or module \fIDevel::MOD\fR.
.TP
.B -D\fR[\fInumber/letters\fR]
Set debugging flags.
.TP
.B -u
Dump core after parsing program.
.SH INPUT PROCESSING
.TP
.B -n
Assume \fBwhile (<>) { ... }\fR loop around program.
.TP
.B -p
Like \fB-n\fR but print each \fB$_\fR after the loop body (sed-style).
.TP
.B -a
Autosplit mode (splits \fB$_\fR into \fB@F\fR).
.TP
.B -F\fI/pattern/\fR
\fBsplit()\fR pattern for \fB-a\fR.
.TP
.B -l\fR[\fIoctnum\fR]
Enable line ending processing.
.TP
.B -0\fR[\fIoctal\fR]
Specify record separator (\fB\\0\fR if no arg).
.TP
.B -g
Slurp all input at once (alias for \fB-0777\fR).
.TP
.B -i\fR[\fIextension\fR]
Edit \fB<>\fR files in place; backup if extension supplied; multiple files
processed in parallel.
.SH MODULES & PATHS
.TP
.B -M \fIMODULE\fR
Execute \fBuse \fImodule\fB...\fR before program.
.TP
.B -m \fIMODULE\fR
Execute \fBuse \fImodule\fB ()\fR before program (no import).
.TP
.B -I \fIDIRECTORY\fR
Specify \fB@INC\fR directory (several allowed).
.TP
.B -f
Don't do \fI$sitelib/sitecustomize.pl\fR at startup.
.TP
.B -S
Look for programfile using \fB$PATH\fR.
.TP
.B -x\fR[\fIdirectory\fR]
Ignore text before \fB#!perl\fR line.
.SH UNICODE & SAFETY
.TP
.B -C\fR[\fInumber/list\fR]
Enable listed Unicode features.
.TP
.B -t
Enable tainting warnings.
.TP
.B -T
Enable tainting checks.
.TP
.B -U
Allow unsafe operations.
.TP
.B -s
Enable switch parsing for programfile args.
.SH WARNINGS
.TP
.B -w
Enable many useful warnings.
.TP
.B -W
Enable all warnings.
.TP
.B -X
Disable all warnings.
.SH INFO
.TP
.B -v
Print version, patchlevel and license.
.TP
.B -V\fR[\fB:\fIconfigvar\fR]
Print configuration summary.
.TP
.BR -h ", " --help
Print help.
.SH PARALLEL EXTENSIONS
.TP
.B -j \fIN\fR
Set number of parallel threads (rayon pool).
.TP
.BR pmap " {BLOCK} @list [, progress => EXPR]"
Parallel map; optional stderr progress bar.
.TP
.BR pmap_chunked " N {BLOCK} @list"
Parallel map in batches of N items per thread.
.TP
.BR pcache " {BLOCK} @list"
Parallel memoize (key = stringified topic).
.TP
.BR par_lines " PATH, CODE [, progress => EXPR]"
mmap + parallel line scan (interpreter).
.TP
.BR par_walk " PATH, CODE"
Parallel recursive dir walk; topic is each path.
.TP
.BR par_sed " PATTERN, REPLACEMENT, FILES..."
Parallel in-place regex replace per file (g flag).
.TP
.BR pipeline " @list ->filter/map/take/collect"
Lazy iterator (runs on collect); chain
.B ->pmap/pgrep/pfor/pmap_chunked/psort/pcache/preduce
like top-level p* functions.
.TP
.BR par_pipeline " @list" \fIsame chain\fR
Filter / map parallel on collect (order kept).
.B par_pipeline(source=>...,stages=>...,workers=>...)
for explicit channel stages.
.TP
.BR async " {BLOCK}"
Run block on a worker thread; returns a task handle.
.TP
.BR spawn " {BLOCK}"
Rust-style alias for \fBasync\fR; join with \fBawait\fR.
.TP
.BR await " EXPR"
Join async task; passes through non-task values.
.TP
.BR pgrep " {BLOCK} @list"
Parallel grep across all cores.
.TP
.BR pfor " {BLOCK} @list"
Parallel foreach.
.TP
.BR psort " {BLOCK} @list"
Parallel sort.
.TP
.BR preduce " {BLOCK} @list"
Parallel tree fold (rayon; associative ops only).
.TP
.BR preduce_init " EXPR, {BLOCK} @list"
Parallel fold with explicit identity.
.TP
.BR pmap_reduce " {MAP} {REDUCE} @list"
Fused parallel map + tree reduce.
.TP
.BR fan " [N] {BLOCK}"
Execute BLOCK N times (default N = rayon pool size).
\fB$_\fR is the index.
.TP
.BR fan_cap " [N] {BLOCK}"
Like \fBfan\fR; returns list of block return values (index order).
.SH SKETCH ALGEBRA
Probabilistic data structures are first-class operands for
.BR + " | & ^ - " .
World-first \(em no other language treats these as syntactic
primitives. Operators are functional; neither operand is mutated.
.TP
.B $bloom_a + $bloom_b
Bloom-filter union (also
.BR | ).
.TP
.B $hll_a + $hll_b
HyperLogLog union (also
.BR | ).
.TP
.B $cms_a + $cms_b
Count-Min Sketch pointwise counter sum.
.TP
.B $topk_a + $topk_b
SpaceSaving heavy-hitter merge.
.TP
.B $td_a + $td_b
t-digest centroid merge.
.TP
.B $rb_a | $rb_b
Roaring union (also
.BR + ).
.TP
.B $rb_a & $rb_b
Roaring intersection.
.TP
.B $rb_a ^ $rb_b
Roaring symmetric difference.
.TP
.B $rb_a - $rb_b
Roaring andnot (set difference).
.PP
Shape mismatch (HLL precision differs, Bloom capacity differs)
falls back to the default numeric/bitwise path \(em no panic, no
silent truncation.
.SH RKYV KV STORE
First-class CRUD store with rkyv as the on-disk and on-wire codec.
World-first \(em no other scripting language ships a zero-copy
archive KV as core builtins. Reads are
.RB mmap " + " validate " + " cast
(same primitive
.B script_cache.rs
already uses for cached bytecode); no parse, no allocate per row.
.TP
.B kv_open(\fIpath\fR)
Open or create a store; returns a handle. Missing file
\(em empty store, no I/O until first commit.
.TP
.BR kv_put "(\fIstore\fR, \fIkey\fR, \fIvalue\fR)"
Write key\(rA value. Returns the previous value or
.BR undef .
.TP
.BR kv_get "(\fIstore\fR, \fIkey\fR)"
Return the value or
.BR undef .
Arrays come back as arrayrefs, hashes as hashrefs.
.TP
.BR kv_del "(\fIstore\fR, \fIkey\fR)"
Delete. Returns 1 if the key existed, 0 otherwise.
.TP
.BR kv_exists "(\fIstore\fR, \fIkey\fR)"
1 / 0.
.TP
.BR kv_keys "(\fIstore\fR [, \fIprefix\fR])"
Sorted keys, optional prefix filter.
.TP
.BR kv_scan "(\fIstore\fR, \fIprefix\fR)"
Array of
.RB [ key ", " value ]
arrayref pairs.
.TP
.BR kv_len "(\fIstore\fR)"
Entry count.
.TP
.BR kv_commit "(\fIstore\fR)"
Atomic rewrite to disk (tmp + rename).
.TP
.BR kv_batch "(\fIstore\fR, [[\fBop\fR, \fIk\fR, \fIv\fR], ...])"
All-or-nothing multi-op; rolls back the in-memory state if any op rejects.
.TP
.BR kv_close "(\fIstore\fR)"
Auto-commits if dirty.
.TP
.BR kv_stats "(\fIstore\fR)"
Hashref of metadata
.RI ( entries ", " commit_count ", " last_commit_secs ", " format_version ", " created_at_secs ", " stryke_version ).
.PP
Storage format is versioned (magic
.B STKV
+
.BR format_version )
so reopening a future store fails fast instead of silently
mis-deserialising. Phase 2 ships
.B stryke kvd
server + remote
.B kv_connect
client over the same archive format.
.SH REPL & SHELL-LIKE BUILTINS
The
.B s
binary doubles as an interactive REPL via reedline:
persistent history, tab completion against the full 22,071-name
corpus, sub-10 ms cold start. Over 80 coreutils-shaped builtins
work as immediately-callable barewords with no fork or exec
(every result is a stryke value, composable with \fB|>\fR pipelines).
.PP
